    <!-- Feeding Tips Descriptions -->
    <string name="desc_exclusive_breastfeeding">Breast milk is the perfect food for your baby. Feed on demand — every 2-3 hours (8-12 times/day). No water, no other foods needed for the first 6 months.</string>
    <string name="desc_breastfeeding_latch">Ensure baby\'s mouth covers the areola (dark area), not just the nipple. A good latch doesn\'t hurt. If it hurts, gently break the latch and try again.</string>
    <string name="desc_night_feeding">Night feeds are important for milk supply. Prolactin (milk-making hormone) is highest at night. Try side-lying position for comfort.</string>
    <string name="desc_starting_solids">At 6 months, introduce soft mashed foods: rice porridge, dal, banana, boiled vegetables. Start with 1-2 teaspoons, gradually increase. Continue breastfeeding.</string>
    <string name="desc_foods_introduce">6-8 months: mashed cereals, vegetables, fruits\n8-10 months: minced meats, eggs, soft finger foods\n10-12 months: family foods (mashed)</string>
    <string name="desc_foods_avoid">❌ Honey (botulism risk)\n❌ Cow\'s milk as main drink\n❌ Added salt or sugar\n❌ Whole nuts (choking)\n❌ Raw eggs</string>
    <string name="desc_iron_rich_foods">Iron is critical for brain development. Good sources: dal (lentils), meat, fortified cereals, leafy greens. Pair with Vitamin C foods (tomato, lemon) to boost absorption.</string>
    <string name="desc_signs_hunger">Early signs: rooting reflex, sucking hands, turning head side to side\nLate signs: crying is a LATE sign — try to feed before crying starts</string>
    <string name="desc_vitamin_d">If exclusively breastfed, give 400 IU Vitamin D drops daily from day 1. Sunlight alone is not enough for dark-skinned babies or babies in northern regions.</string>
    <string name="desc_hydration_toddlers">After 12 months, introduce whole cow\'s milk (limit to 16-24 oz/day). Water is the best drink. Avoid fruit juices — they have high sugar and low nutrition.</string>

